claim.claim-text:
1. A substrate cleaning apparatus for cleaning a substrate comprising: 
a spindle movable in a generally vertical direction and having a substrate supported on an upper end; 
a brush extending in a generally horizontal direction over the substrate; 
a force measuring gage mounted to the spindle for detecting forces applied to the substrate by the brush; and 
a spindle control electrically connected to the force measuring gage and mechanically connected to the spindle, the spindle control causing the spindle to move as a function of forces being applied to the substrate by the brush.

2. A substrate cleaning apparatus for cleaning a substrate comprising: 
a spindle movable in a generally vertical direction and having a substrate supported on an upper end; 
a brush extending in a generally horizontal direction over the substrate, the brush cleaning the substrate in response to the brush and substrate having a contacting relationship; 
a force measuring gage mounted to the spindle for detecting forces applied to the substrate by the brush; 
a spindle drive mechanically coupled to the spindle for moving the spindle in upward and downward directions; and 
a spindle drive control electrically connected to the force measuring gage and the spindle drive and causing the spindle drive to move the spindle as a function of forces being applied to the substrate by the brush.

5. A method of cleaning a substrate supported on an upper end of a spindle comprising: 
positioning a brush at a fixed elevation over the substrate; 
moving the spindle in an upward direction to bring the substrate into contact with the brush; 
measuring a cleaning force on the spindle caused by the brush contacting the substrate; and 
moving the spindle in response to measuring the cleaning force on the substrate caused by the brush.

7. A method of claim 5 further comprising: 
determining a range of acceptable cleaning forces between the cleaning brush and the substrate; 
maintaining the cleaning force on the substrate within the range of acceptable cleaning forces.

15. A method of claim 5 further comprising: 
determining an acceptable cleaning force between the cleaning brush and the substrate; 
maintaining the cleaning force on the substrate substantially equal to the acceptable cleaning force value.
